  "summary": "Inspector Taverner questions the Leonidis family regarding the contents and execution of Aristide Leonidis's will. Roger Leonidis explains that the will provided for Aunt Edith and Aunt Brenda, with the remaining inheritance divided among Roger, Philip, Sophia, and Sophia's children, Ulysses and Josephine. Clementine Leonidis testifies that Aristide signed the document in the presence of two servants, Johnson and Janet Walmer, who also signed as witnesses. The family maintains that Aristide remained at his desk during the signing and that a stack of papers covered the document, preventing the servants from seeing its specific contents.\n\nThe investigation shifts when Taverner presents a document found in Aristide's safe. Mr. Gaskill, the lawyer, is shocked to discover that this document is the original will he prepared, but it is unsigned. This discovery contradicts the family's testimony regarding the witnessed signing. Philip notes that his father suffered from glaucoma and wore high-prescription glasses while signing. Mr. Gaskill observes a specific mark on the document resembling an airplane and concludes that the paper is the original intended will rather than a draft. Taverner suggests that the signed version of the will was switched for this unsigned version.\n\nFollowing the confrontation, the group disperses. The narrator follows Taverner to the Scotland Yard assistant office, where Taverner expresses frustration over the lack of suspicious evidence regarding the family and a young tutor. The narrator encourages Taverner, claiming to have more leads.",
